SIMPLE: embroil
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Embroil
<hw>Em*broil"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Embroiled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Embroiling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>embrouiller</ets>; pref. <ets>em-</ets> (L. <ets>in</ets>) +
<ets>brouiller</ets>. See 1st <er>Broil</er>, and cf.
<er>Imbroglio</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To throw into confusion or
commotion by contention or discord; to entangle in a broil or quarrel;
to make confused; to distract; to involve in difficulties by dissension
or strife.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The royal house <qex>embroiled</qex> in civil war.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To implicate in confusion; to complicate; to
jumble.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Christian antiquities at Rome . . . are so
<qex>embroiled</qex> with fable and legend.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To perplex; entangle; distract; disturb;
disorder; trouble; implicate; commingle.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Embroil</ent>⟦br⟧

